{"primaryContentSections":[{"declarations":[{"tokens":[{"text":"@frozen","kind":"attribute"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PartialRangeFrom","kind":"identifier"},{"text":"<","kind":"text"},{"text":"Bound","kind":"genericParameter"},{"text":"> ","kind":"text"},{"text":"where","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"Bound","kind":"typeIdentifier"},{"text":" : ","kind":"text"},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/Comparable","preciseIdentifier":"s:SL","text":"Comparable","kind":"typeIdentifier"}],"languages":["swift"],"platforms":["macOS"]}],"kind":"declarations"},{"kind":"content","content":[{"text":"Overview","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You create ","type":"text"},{"code":"PartialRangeFrom","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" instances by using the postfix range operator","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"(postfix ","type":"text"},{"code":"...","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":").","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let atLeastFive = 5..."]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You can use a partial range to quickly check if a value is contained in a","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"particular range of values. For example:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["atLeastFive.contains(4)","\/\/ false","atLeastFive.contains(5)","\/\/ true","atLeastFive.contains(6)","\/\/ true"]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"You can use a partial range of a collection’s indices to represent the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"range from the partial range’s lower bound up to the end of the","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"collection.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let numbers = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50, 60, 70]","print(numbers[3...])","\/\/ Prints \"[40, 50, 60, 70]\""]},{"text":"Using a Partial Range as a Sequence","type":"heading","level":2,"anchor":"Using-a-Partial-Range-as-a-Sequence"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"When a partial range uses integers as its lower and upper bounds, or any","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"other type that conforms to the ","type":"text"},{"code":"Strideable","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" protocol with an integer","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"stride, you can use that range in a ","type":"text"},{"code":"for","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":"-","type":"text"},{"code":"in","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" loop or with any sequence","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"method that doesn’t require that the sequence is finite. The elements of","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"a partial range are the consecutive values from its lower bound continuing","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"upward indefinitely.","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["func isTheMagicNumber(_ x: Int) -> Bool {","    return x == 3","}","","for x in 1... {","    if isTheMagicNumber(x) {","        print(\"\\(x) is the magic number!\")","        break","    } else {","        print(\"\\(x) wasn't it...\")","    }","}","\/\/ \"1 wasn't it...\"","\/\/ \"2 wasn't it...\"","\/\/ \"3 is the magic number!\""]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"Because a ","type":"text"},{"code":"PartialRangeFrom","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" sequence counts upward indefinitely, do not","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"use one with methods that read the entire sequence before returning, such","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"as ","type":"text"},{"code":"map(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", ","type":"text"},{"code":"filter(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", or ","type":"text"},{"code":"suffix(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". It is safe to use operations","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"that put an upper limit on the number of elements they access, such as","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"prefix(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" or ","type":"text"},{"code":"dropFirst(_:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":", and operations that you can guarantee","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"will terminate, such as passing a closure you know will eventually return","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"true","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" to ","type":"text"},{"code":"first(where:)","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"In the following example, the ","type":"text"},{"code":"asciiTable","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" sequence is made by zipping","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"together the characters in the ","type":"text"},{"code":"alphabet","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" string with a partial range","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"starting at 65, the ASCII value of the capital letter A. Iterating over","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"two zipped sequences continues only as long as the shorter of the two","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"sequences, so the iteration stops at the end of ","type":"text"},{"code":"alphabet","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]},{"type":"codeListing","syntax":"swift","code":["let alphabet = \"ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZ\"","let asciiTable = zip(65..., alphabet)","for (code, letter) in asciiTable {","    print(code, letter)","}","\/\/ \"65 A\"","\/\/ \"66 B\"","\/\/ \"67 C\"","\/\/ ...","\/\/ \"89 Y\"","\/\/ \"90 Z\""]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The behavior of incrementing indefinitely is determined by the type of","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"Bound","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":". For example, iterating over an instance of","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"code":"PartialRangeFrom<Int>","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" traps when the sequence’s next value would be","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"above ","type":"text"},{"code":"Int.max","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":".","type":"text"}]}]}],"sections":[],"metadata":{"externalID":"s:s16PartialRangeFromV","title":"PartialRangeFrom","roleHeading":"Structure","platforms":[{"beta":false,"name":"iOS","introducedAt":"8.0","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false},{"beta":false,"name":"iPadOS","introducedAt":"8.0","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false},{"beta":false,"name":"Mac Catalyst","introducedAt":"13.0","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false},{"beta":false,"name":"macOS","introducedAt":"10.10","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false},{"beta":false,"name":"tvOS","introducedAt":"9.0","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false},{"beta":false,"name":"visionOS","introducedAt":"1.0","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false},{"beta":false,"name":"watchOS","introducedAt":"2.0","deprecated":false,"unavailable":false}],"fragments":[{"text":"struct","kind":"keyword"},{"text":" ","kind":"text"},{"text":"PartialRangeFrom","kind":"identifier"}],"symbolKind":"struct","role":"symbol","navigatorTitle":[{"text":"PartialRangeFrom","kind":"identifier"}],"modules":[{"name":"Swift"}]},"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift"]]},"abstract":[{"text":"A partial interval extending upward from a lower bound.","type":"text"}],"relationshipsSections":[{"type":"conformsTo","kind":"relationships","identifiers":["doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/Copyable","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/Decodable","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/Encodable","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/Escapable","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/RangeExpression","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/Sendable","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documentation\/Swift\/SendableMetatype","doc:\/\/com.apple.Swift\/documenta